  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">PLEASE READ BEFORE REVIEWING<br>
<br>
This is my first deck.  And the answer to many of the questions that you might ask is &quot;My resources are limited.&quot;  I don&#39;t have a single rare Legolas, Aragorn, Boromir, or Arwen.  I only have one Servant of the Secret Fire.  I have no Goblin Armories.  Still, this is the best deck I can put together.  So, hopefully, I&#39;ve answered any questions.  Now, I&#39;ll welcome any suggestions, regardless of whether I have the cards or not.  I&#39;m trying to gather the resources to make a good deck, so please don&#39;t hesitate to throw out ideas, if you think they&#39;ll help with what I&#39;m trying to do.<br>
<br>
WHAT DOES THE DECK DO?<br>
First and foremost, the deck goes first.  You bid 5 or 6 burdens, pull Sam immediately and exhaust him.  This takes away the Prancing Pony start and it gives you a sacrificial lamb.  Sam&#39;s only purpose is to secure the first turn start.  This gets you a head start.  The Moria portion of the deck is meant to do a few things.  It cycles the deck quickly.  Using Goblin Scavengers, Goblin Scimitars, Goblin Swarms, and Host of Thousands, you shoudl be playing your Goblin Scimitars over and over and over again.  This gets through the deck quickly, so by site 4 or 5, you should have a Cave Troll and a Hammer or Keyward (quite possibly both).  This will slow down your opponent underground.  Nobody&#39;s going to move with the Cave Troll breathing down their neck.  And by cycling with my shadow, I also get to my good fellowship cards more quickly.  This means, I&#39;m more likely to have the cards I need when I need them.  Now, you might have noticed the Shoulder to Shoulder.  I use this to beef up Gimli.  With Gimli&#39;s text and Shoulder to Shoulder, Gimli should be able to win any skirmish by exerting other companions or allies to make Gimli Strength +2.  And if that fails you&#39;ve still got a beefed up Aragorn and Gandalf to win some skirmishes.  In a nutshell, that&#39;s what the deck does.<br>
<br>
So, there you have it.  That&#39;s what my deck does.  Please, I would appreciate any suggestions or criticisms (so long as their constructive).  Thanks for reading.<br>
<br>
Devon &quot;I hope to start writing articles and TRs soon&quot; Clark </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
